Graphite was found to be the most satisfactory
material in which to collect the 15N. Saturation was
found at one nitrogen atom per four carbon atoms.
The probable error for the absolute value
of the elastic cross section is about 11%, the major
source of which is in evaluation of number of 15N
atoms per unit area in the target. Other contributing
factors are uncertainties in measuring areas
under the 15N peaks, and in calibration of the current
spectrometer. A 2% error is estimated for relative
values at the same angle and for energy differences
not greater than 50 keV. This estimate rises to 12%
for large differences in energy and angle.
